258. Add Digits (LeetCode)Easy    Digital Root (GFG)
Hint
Given an integer num, repeatedly add all its digits until the result has only one digit, and return it.

Example 1:
Input: num = 38
Output: 2
Explanation: The process is
38 --> 3 + 8 --> 11
11 --> 1 + 1 --> 2 
Since 2 has only one digit, return it.
Example 2:

Input: num = 0
Output: 0

import java.util.*;
class Main {
    public static int adddigits(int num){
        if(num == 0){
            return 0;
        }
        // return(num % 9 == 0) ?9: num % 9; Easy to use 
        /*
How it Works 
1. The Structure The ternary operator follows this pattern:Condition ? Value_if_True : Value_if_False 
2. The Logic in your code The code is handling a specific rule of Digital Roots: the digital root of any multiple of 9 (like 9, 18, 27) is always 9, but the modulo operator % would return 0. 
Part of Code 
What it meansn % 9 == 0
The Condition: Is the remainder of \(n % 9\) equal to zero (i.e., Is \(n\) a multiple of 9?)? 9If True: If it is a multiple of 9, return 9.: (n % 9)If False: If it is NOT a multiple of 9, return the actual remainder.
        */
        else if(num % 9 == 0){
            return 9;
        }
        else{
            return num % 9;
        }
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int n = 34;
        System.out.println(adddigits(n));
    }
}
